TITLE = "What are Simultaneous Equations?"

SECTIONS = [
    {
        "title": "One Equation, Infinite Solutions",
        "body": "<p>Consider a single equation with two unknowns:</p><div class='concept-box'><p>\\(x + y = 10\\)</p></div><p>How many pairs (x, y) satisfy this? Infinitely many!</p><ul><li>x = 1, y = 9 ✓</li><li>x = 2, y = 8 ✓</li><li>x = 3, y = 7 ✓</li><li>x = 5.5, y = 4.5 ✓</li><li>... and infinitely more</li></ul><p>Each solution lies on a line when we graph it. One equation gives us a line; two unknowns cannot be uniquely pinned down.</p>"
    },
    {
        "title": "Two Equations, One Solution",
        "body": "<p>Now add a second equation:</p><div class='concept-box'><p>\\(x + y = 10\\)<br>\\(x - y = 2\\)</p></div><p>Now we need BOTH to be true simultaneously. Let's test some pairs:</p><ul><li>x = 1, y = 9: First equation 1 + 9 = 10 ✓, but second 1 - 9 = -8 ✗</li><li>x = 6, y = 4: First equation 6 + 4 = 10 ✓, and second 6 - 4 = 2 ✓</li></ul><p>When we have two equations with two unknowns (and they are not parallel or identical), there is exactly ONE solution. The two lines intersect at one point.</p><div class='success-box'><p><strong>First Principle:</strong> Two independent linear equations with two unknowns have exactly one unique solution—the point where the two lines intersect on a graph.</p></div>"
    },
    {
        "title": "Checking if a Solution Works",
        "body": "<p>To verify a solution, substitute the values into BOTH equations and check if both become true.</p><div class='worked-example'><p><strong>Example:</strong> Do x = 2, y = 1 solve the system?</p><p>\\(2x + y = 5\\) and \\(x + y = 3\\)</p><p>Substitute x = 2, y = 1:</p><ul><li>First: 2(2) + 1 = 5 ✓</li><li>Second: 2 + 1 = 3 ✓</li></ul><p>Yes! Both equations are satisfied.</p></div><p>If even one equation fails, the pair is not a solution.</p>"
    },
    {
        "title": "Why We Need Simultaneous Equations",
        "body": "<p>Real-world problems often have multiple constraints that must ALL be satisfied together:</p><ul><li><strong>Business:</strong> A company needs to find a price and quantity that satisfy both cost constraints AND profit targets.</li><li><strong>Transport:</strong> Two vehicles start from different points and meet—you need both distance equations.</li><li><strong>Money:</strong> You know the total cost of items AND how much more one costs than another—two conditions, two equations.</li></ul><p>Without simultaneous equations, we only have partial information. With them, we find THE answer that satisfies everything.</p>"
    }
]
